## Abstract

Autonomous navigation of quadrotor unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs) in environments where Global Navigation Satellite System (GNSS) signals are unavailable remains a significant challenge for applications in indoor inspection, search-and-rescue, and subterranean mapping. Traditional flight controllers rely on GPS-derived position feedback, which is absent in indoor facilities, tunnels, and urban canyons. This project presents the design, implementation, and evaluation of a deep reinforcement learning (RL) framework that enables a simulated quadrotor to navigate obstacle-rich environments without GNSS, using only a forward-facing depth camera and a simulated visual-inertial odometry (VIO) pipeline for state estimation. The system is developed in Microsoft AirSim and employs Proximal Policy Optimisation (PPO) with a multi-input observation space comprising 84x84 depth images (four-frame stack) and body-frame velocity estimates subject to realistic drift and bias injection. A four-layer safety monitor enforces velocity clamping, proximity-based braking, altitude guarding, and emergency stop during deployment. Domain randomisation -- including depth sensor noise, spawn jitter, VIO drift, and optical flow noise -- is applied to improve policy robustness for sim-to-real transfer. The trained policy is exported via ONNX for deployment on the Quanser QDrone 2 platform (NVIDIA Jetson Xavier NX, Intel RealSense depth camera). Preliminary simulation results demonstrate that the PPO agent learns effective forward-flight obstacle avoidance with decreasing collision rates over training. This report details the system architecture, training methodology, evaluation protocol, and preliminary simulation results, and discusses the planned hardware validation on the QDrone 2.

---

## 1. Introduction

### 1.1 Motivation

Quadrotor UAVs have become indispensable tools across inspection, logistics, search-and-rescue, and environmental monitoring [1]. Their mechanical simplicity, vertical take-off and landing capability, and agility in confined spaces make them well suited to indoor operations. However, indoor and underground environments -- such as parking structures, warehouses, tunnels, and urban canyons -- share a critical limitation: GNSS signals are unavailable, unreliable, or intentionally jammed [2]. In these GNSS-denied conditions, conventional autopilot systems that depend on GPS for position hold and waypoint navigation fail entirely. The UAV must therefore rely exclusively on onboard sensing and computation for both state estimation and navigation.

The challenge of GNSS-denied flight is not merely academic. Industrial inspection of oil and gas infrastructure, post-disaster reconnaissance inside collapsed buildings, and security patrol of underground car parks all require autonomous UAV operation without satellite positioning. The global market for inspection drones alone is projected to exceed $12 billion by 2028, with a substantial fraction of applications occurring in GPS-degraded environments [1]. Current practice relies on skilled human pilots using manual line-of-sight control, which is dangerous, fatiguing, and does not scale. An autonomous system capable of navigating without GPS would therefore address a genuine engineering need.

Traditional quadrotor control architectures employ cascaded Proportional-Integral-Derivative (PID) controllers for attitude, velocity, and position stabilisation [3]. While effective for trajectory tracking when accurate state estimates are available, PID controllers require manual gain tuning for each airframe, offer limited adaptability to environmental disturbances such as wind gusts or payload changes, and cannot independently generate navigation decisions in unknown environments. Model Predictive Control (MPC) extends classical control by optimising over a receding horizon, but requires an accurate dynamics model and is computationally expensive for real-time deployment on embedded platforms [3].

Reinforcement learning (RL) offers a fundamentally different paradigm: rather than specifying a control law explicitly, an RL agent learns an optimal policy through trial-and-error interaction with its environment, guided by a scalar reward signal [4]. The agent does not require a dynamics model and can, in principle, discover control strategies that are difficult to engineer manually. Recent advances in deep RL -- particularly Proximal Policy Optimisation (PPO) [5] and Soft Actor-Critic (SAC) [6] -- have demonstrated promising results for robotic locomotion, dexterous manipulation, and, more recently, UAV attitude control and navigation [7][8]. PPO is an on-policy algorithm that constrains policy updates via a clipped surrogate objective, providing stable training without the complexity of trust-region methods. SAC is an off-policy maximum-entropy algorithm that encourages exploration and has demonstrated superior sample efficiency in continuous control tasks.

A persistent barrier to deploying RL policies on physical robots is the sim-to-real gap: policies trained in simulation often fail on hardware due to differences in physics modelling, sensor noise characteristics, and actuation dynamics [9]. Domain randomisation -- systematically varying simulation parameters during training -- has emerged as a practical technique for bridging this gap [10]. By exposing the agent to a distribution of environments during training, the policy learns representations that are invariant to the specific parameters of any single environment, including the real world. Microsoft AirSim provides a high-fidelity Unreal Engine-based simulation environment with realistic rendering, physics, and configurable sensor models, making it a suitable platform for training RL policies before physical deployment [11].

### 1.2 Research Gap

The existing literature on RL-based UAV control has predominantly focused on outdoor environments with GPS-aided state estimation, or has used ground-truth simulator state as the observation input without acknowledging the GNSS-denied premise [8][12]. Studies that explicitly address GNSS-denied flight tend to focus on localisation and state estimation (visual-inertial odometry, simultaneous localisation and mapping) rather than end-to-end navigation policy learning [2][13]. A gap exists at the intersection of these two threads: RL-based navigation where the agent observes only depth imagery and VIO-estimated velocity -- with realistic drift and bias -- rather than perfect simulator state. Furthermore, few works combine domain randomisation of both sensor noise and state estimation error with a structured, independently verifiable safety monitor for deployment. This project aims to bridge that gap by training an RL agent whose observation space faithfully reflects the information available on a real GNSS-denied platform, and by wrapping the learned policy in a safety architecture suitable for physical flight testing.

### 1.3 Contributions

This project makes the following contributions:

- **Design and implement** a Gymnasium-compatible AirSim environment wrapper with lockstep simulation, configurable reward functions, and multi-waypoint goal navigation, validated by 147 unit tests.
- **Develop a simulated VIO pipeline** that replaces GPS ground-truth velocity with drift-corrupted, bias-injected estimates, enforcing the GNSS-denied constraint within the training loop itself rather than as a post-hoc claim.
- **Train and evaluate** a PPO-based navigation policy using a multi-input observation space (depth images + VIO velocity) with domain randomisation across four sensor and estimation parameters.
- **Implement a four-layer safety monitor** (velocity clamping, proximity braking, altitude guard, emergency stop) that wraps the learned policy during deployment, architecturally separated from the policy.
- **Establish a sim-to-real pipeline** via ONNX export and ROS2 deployment architecture targeting the Quanser QDrone 2 with NVIDIA Jetson Xavier NX and Intel RealSense D435i depth camera.

### 1.4 Report Structure

The remainder of this report is organised as follows. Section 2 reviews prior work on RL for UAV navigation, GNSS-denied state estimation, simulation-based training, domain randomisation, and hybrid control architectures. Section 3 presents the system methodology, including the observation and action spaces, reward formulation, simulated VIO model, domain randomisation strategy, and safety architecture. Section 4 describes the software implementation, training pipeline, and evaluation protocol. Section 5 presents preliminary results and discusses their interpretation, limitations, and implications. Section 6 identifies project risks and their mitigation strategies. Section 7 provides a reflective summary addressing personal development, sustainability, ethics, and equality. Section 8 concludes the report with a summary of contributions, acknowledged limitations, and specific future work.

