## 2. Literature Review

### 2.1 Reinforcement Learning for UAV Navigation

Reinforcement learning has been applied to quadrotor control across a spectrum from low-level attitude regulation to high-level navigation planning. Koch et al. [7] demonstrated that RL could learn stable attitude control for quadrotors, achieving performance comparable to hand-tuned PID controllers in both simulation and physical experiments. Their work validated that deep RL methods can handle the fast dynamics of multirotor systems, though they relied on full state feedback rather than sensor-only observations. Hwangbo et al. [14] extended policy gradient methods to full position control of a quadrotor, reporting successful sim-to-real transfer for hover stabilisation using an Iterative Learning Controller (ILC) to refine the policy. Their transfer methodology demonstrated that careful system identification can complement domain randomisation for bridging the simulation gap.

Camci and Kayacan [12] explored end-to-end motion planning where a deep network directly outputs thrust and angular rate commands from system state, demonstrating the potential of RL to replace traditional planning pipelines. However, their approach used privileged state information not available on real hardware without GPS. Singla et al. [15] proposed a memory-based deep RL method using recurrent neural networks with monocular camera input, addressing partial observability in indoor environments. This is particularly relevant to GNSS-denied scenarios where the agent cannot observe its absolute position. Shin [8] applied RL to quadrotor control in AirSim and demonstrated deep RL for obstacle avoidance in a related study [16], providing a template for simulation-only RL training. Wei et al. [25] demonstrated imitation learning for vision-based UAV navigation, though RL has advantages in environments where expert demonstrations are difficult to obtain.

These works confirm that RL can learn complex UAV behaviours without explicit dynamic models. However, they typically assume access to accurate state information -- either from GPS or from ground-truth simulator readings -- which is unavailable in GNSS-denied scenarios. The present project differs by using VIO-estimated velocity as the sole proprioceptive input during training, with intentional drift and bias injection. This forces the policy to develop robustness to state estimation error, which is a practical requirement for real GNSS-denied deployment.

### 2.2 GNSS-Denied Navigation and State Estimation

Cheng et al. [2] provide a comprehensive survey of UAV autonomous navigation under GPS-denied conditions, classifying approaches as map-based (SLAM, pre-built maps) and mapless (visual odometry, learning-based). Vision-based methods are attractive due to the low mass and power consumption of cameras, though they are sensitive to illumination changes, textureless surfaces, and motion blur. Within GNSS-denied localisation, Gallo and Barrientos [13] proposed a semi-direct visual navigation scheme aided by a PI-inspired inertial prior to reduce visual odometry drift for aerial vehicles. Their system achieved metre-level accuracy over multi-minute flights but required significant computational resources for feature extraction and matching. Kinnari et al. [17] addressed season-invariant GNSS-denied visual localisation using learned feature descriptors, demonstrating robustness to appearance changes across seasons.

These approaches produce relatively accurate pose estimates but still require a separate guidance and control layer to translate position estimates into navigation commands. The present project takes a different but complementary approach: rather than implementing a full VIO pipeline (e.g., VINS-Mono or ORB-SLAM3), the system simulates VIO behaviour by corrupting ground-truth velocity with Gaussian drift and per-episode bias. This provides the RL agent with a training signal that reflects the noise characteristics of real VIO systems while remaining computationally tractable and deterministic for reproducible training. The simulated VIO model is parameterised by drift rate and bias magnitude, which can be calibrated against a specific VIO implementation during hardware integration.

### 2.3 Simulation-Based Training and AirSim

High-fidelity simulation has become standard practice for developing learning-based UAV controllers, as real-world training is expensive, slow, and carries risk of hardware damage. AirSim [11], built on Unreal Engine 4, offers photorealistic rendering alongside physics and sensor models for multirotor and fixed-wing platforms. Its API supports programmatic control of vehicles, cameras, weather conditions, and simulation stepping, making it well suited for automated RL training loops. Madaan et al. [18] demonstrated AirSim's capabilities through the Drone Racing Lab, a standardised benchmark for autonomous drone racing. Chan et al. [19] surveyed RL-based drone simulators and identified AirSim as particularly suitable for vision-based RL research due to its rendering fidelity and API extensibility, though they noted its computational overhead relative to lighter simulators. Gaigalas [20] proposed a framework for vision-based autonomous UAV navigation combining simulation-first development with structured evaluation protocols.

This project follows the simulation-first philosophy: all controller tuning, policy training, and evaluation are conducted in AirSim before any hardware deployment. Two AirSim environments are used -- AirSim Neighbourhood (outdoor, open terrain with buildings and vegetation) and Blocks (indoor, cluttered with geometric obstacles) -- with round-robin rotation during training to promote generalisation across obstacle densities and visual appearances. The simulation uses lockstep stepping to ensure deterministic training: at each control step, the simulation is paused, the agent selects an action, the action is applied, the simulation advances by a fixed time increment (dt = 0.1 s), and the new observation is captured. This eliminates variable frame-rate effects that could introduce non-stationarity into the training process.

### 2.4 Domain Randomisation for Sim-to-Real Transfer

Tobin et al. [10] introduced domain randomisation as a method for transferring deep neural networks from simulation to the real world by training on a wide distribution of visual and physical parameters. The key insight is that if the simulation distribution is sufficiently broad, the real world appears as just another sample from the training distribution. Sadeghi and Levine [21] demonstrated that policies trained entirely in randomised simulation could transfer to real indoor environments for collision avoidance using monocular RGB images, without any real-world fine-tuning. Peng et al. [22] extended domain randomisation to dynamics parameters (mass, friction, damping) for robotic manipulation, showing that randomising physics alongside visuals is critical for robust transfer.

In the present project, domain randomisation is applied across four axes: (1) depth sensor noise (Gaussian, sigma = 0.02 normalised units), simulating the stochastic errors in structured-light and time-of-flight depth sensors; (2) spawn position (uniform disk, R = 5.0 m) and yaw (uniform [0, 2pi)), preventing the agent from memorising starting conditions; (3) VIO drift per step (Gaussian, sigma = 0.01 m/s per axis), simulating accumulating dead-reckoning error; and (4) optical flow noise (Gaussian, sigma = 0.03), simulating the noise floor of optical flow sensors used in some VIO implementations. This multi-axis strategy aims to produce policies that remain effective across the distribution of conditions encountered during real-world deployment on the Quanser QDrone 2, where sensor noise, estimation error, and environmental conditions will differ from any single simulation configuration.

### 2.5 Hybrid Control Architectures and Safety

In practical UAV systems, high-level perception and decision-making are typically separated from low-level attitude stabilisation and motor mixing [23]. This separation provides modularity, allows each layer to be developed and validated independently, and ensures that a failure in the high-level system does not destabilise the vehicle's fundamental flight dynamics. Mellinger and Kumar [23] established the standard cascaded architecture for quadrotor control: a trajectory planner generates position references, a position controller converts these to attitude commands, and an attitude controller drives the motor speeds.

The present project adopts this hybrid pattern with the RL agent operating at the velocity command level. The policy outputs body-frame velocity commands (forward, lateral, yaw rate) at each timestep. These commands are executed by AirSim's internal flight controller via moveByVelocityZBodyFrameAsync, which handles attitude stabilisation and maintains a fixed altitude. This design choice means the RL agent does not need to learn basic flight stabilisation -- a well-solved problem in classical control -- but instead focuses its learning capacity on navigation-level obstacle avoidance and goal-seeking, where learning-based methods offer clear advantages over classical approaches.

Between the policy output and the low-level controller, a four-layer safety monitor enforces physical constraints. This architecturally separate safety system is essential for physical deployment, where policy errors could result in hardware damage or injury. The monitor's layers -- velocity clamping, proximity braking, altitude guarding, and emergency stop -- operate independently and sequentially, providing defence-in-depth. Even if one layer fails to catch an unsafe command, subsequent layers provide backup protection. This approach follows established practices in safety-critical autonomous systems, where runtime monitors provide an independently verifiable safety guarantee [23].

---

## 3. Methodology

### 3.1 System Architecture

The system follows a modular five-layer architecture designed for clarity of responsibility and independent validation. The simulation layer provides physics simulation through AirSim with lockstep stepping via simContinueForTime(dt) for deterministic training, ensuring that each training episode is reproducible given the same random seed. The perception layer captures depth images from a forward-facing camera at 84x84 resolution, clipped at 20 m maximum range and normalised to [0, 1], with four consecutive frames stacked to provide temporal context for motion estimation. The state estimation layer implements a simulated VIO module that corrupts ground-truth body-frame velocity with Gaussian drift (accumulating over time) and per-episode IMU bias, replacing the GPS-dependent velocity feedback that would be unavailable on a real GNSS-denied platform. The policy layer implements a PPO agent with a MultiInputPolicy architecture: a NatureCNN [26] branch processes the depth image stack and a separate MLP branch processes the velocity vector, with late fusion before the actor and critic heads. The safety layer implements a four-component monitor that enforces velocity limits, proximity-based braking, altitude guarding, and emergency stop conditions.

[PLACEHOLDER: Figure 1 -- System architecture block diagram showing the five layers and data flow from AirSim through perception, VIO, policy, safety monitor, to actuator commands. Include depth camera, VIO module, NatureCNN, MLP, fusion layer, actor/critic heads, and safety monitor components.]

### 3.2 Observation and Action Spaces

The observation space is defined as a gymnasium.spaces.Dict containing two components, reflecting the multi-modal sensing available on the target platform. The image component is a tensor of dimensions 84 x 84 x 4, representing four stacked depth frames. Each frame is captured from AirSim's depth perspective camera, clipped at a maximum range of 20 m (beyond which objects are not relevant for obstacle avoidance), and normalised to [0, 1] by dividing by the clip distance. The four-frame stack, implemented via VecFrameStack, provides the policy with temporal information about obstacle motion without requiring an explicit recurrent architecture. The velocity component is a three-dimensional vector [vx, vy, yaw_rate] in the body frame, obtained from the simulated VIO module rather than from ground-truth AirSim kinematics. When VIO is disabled for ablation purposes, ground-truth velocity rotated into the body frame using the current yaw angle is used instead.

The action space is a continuous Box([-1, 1]^3) mapped to physical velocity commands through linear scaling: vx = a_vx * 3.0 m/s (forward/backward), vy = a_vy * 1.0 m/s (lateral), yaw_rate = a_yaw * 45 deg/s (rotation). The asymmetric scaling between forward and lateral axes reflects the typical operational profile of inspection UAVs, which predominantly fly forward. The maximum velocities were selected based on the Quanser QDrone 2's operational envelope and indoor safety considerations. Commands are issued via moveByVelocityZBodyFrameAsync, which delegates attitude control and altitude hold to AirSim's internal PID controller, maintaining the UAV at a fixed height of -3.0 m (NED convention).

### 3.3 Reward Function Design

Two reward functions are implemented to support different training objectives. The exploration reward function comprises four additive terms:

r_t = w_progress * max(0, vx_body) + w_collision * I_collision + w_smoothness * ||a_t - a_{t-1}|| + w_drift * e_VIO

The progress term (w_progress = 0.5) rewards forward body-frame velocity, with the max(0, ...) clamp added after an early training run produced a degenerate policy that flew backward to minimise collision risk while technically maximising negative progress reward. The collision term (w_collision = -100) applies a large terminal penalty upon collision, detected via AirSim's collision API with timestamp filtering to prevent stale collision flags from erroneously terminating new episodes. The smoothness term (w_smoothness = -0.1) penalises the L2 norm of action differences between consecutive timesteps, discouraging jerky control inputs that stress mechanical components. The drift penalty term (w_drift = -0.1) penalises accumulated VIO estimation error, incentivising the agent to complete tasks efficiently before drift degrades its state estimate.

The waypoint reward function extends the exploration reward with three additional components for goal-directed navigation: a heading alignment term (cosine of bearing angle to the current waypoint), a distance-based potential shaping term (rewarding decrease in normalised distance to the waypoint), a per-waypoint arrival bonus (w_goal = 10), and a mission completion bonus (w_mission = 50) for reaching all waypoints. All reward weights are configurable via YAML files under configs/rewards/, enabling systematic reward ablation studies without code changes.

### 3.4 Simulated Visual-Inertial Odometry

The SimulatedVIO module is the mechanism by which the GNSS-denied constraint is enforced during training. Rather than providing the agent with perfect velocity from AirSim's physics engine -- which would be equivalent to GPS-aided navigation -- the module computes a corrupted velocity estimate:

v_hat_t = v_GT_t + epsilon_accum_t + b_episode

where v_GT_t is the ground-truth velocity rotated into the body frame using the current yaw angle, epsilon_accum_t is an accumulated Gaussian drift term that grows as a random walk over time (sigma_step = 0.01 m/s per axis per step), and b_episode is a per-episode bias vector sampled from N(0, sigma_bias = 0.005 m/s) at the start of each episode. At each episode reset, the accumulated drift is cleared and a new bias is sampled, simulating the re-initialisation that occurs when a real VIO pipeline is restarted.

The module also maintains an integrated position estimate by accumulating velocity times dt, producing a position trajectory that drifts from ground truth over time. This enables computation of the localisation drift metric -- the Euclidean distance between estimated and true position at each timestep -- which quantifies how well the VIO-trained policy tolerates increasing estimation error. Additional optical flow noise (sigma_flow = 0.03) is injected when domain randomisation is active, simulating the noise floor of optical flow sensors used in some VIO implementations. This model captures three key VIO characteristics -- unbounded drift, per-session bias, and noisy instantaneous estimates -- while remaining computationally lightweight and deterministic given a fixed random seed.

### 3.5 Domain Randomisation Strategy

Domain randomisation is applied across four axes to maximise the probability that the trained policy will transfer to the real QDrone 2 platform. At each episode reset, the spawn position is uniformly sampled within a 5.0 m radius disk and the spawn yaw is uniformly sampled from [0, 2pi), preventing the agent from memorising a single starting configuration. A new VIO bias vector is sampled from N(0, 0.005) for each episode. At each timestep within an episode, Gaussian noise (sigma = 0.02 normalised units) is added to the depth image, simulating the stochastic errors characteristic of Intel RealSense structured-light depth sensors. VIO drift noise (sigma = 0.01 m/s per axis) is accumulated at each step, and optical flow noise (sigma = 0.03) is injected into the velocity observation. All randomisation parameters are specified in configs/train_ppo_dr.yaml and can be adjusted without code changes.

The randomisation strategy is designed to be conservative: parameters were chosen to slightly exceed the expected noise levels on the QDrone 2, following the principle that over-randomisation during training produces more robust transfer than under-randomisation, at the potential cost of reduced peak performance in the nominal simulation [10].

### 3.6 Safety Monitor Architecture

The safety monitor implements four sequential checks, each operating independently. First, velocity clamping enforces hard limits on the commanded velocity (vx_max = 3.0 m/s, vy_max = 1.0 m/s, yaw_rate_max = 45 deg/s), ensuring that no policy output can exceed the physical capabilities of the QDrone 2 regardless of the policy's behaviour. Second, proximity braking examines the centre 30% region of interest (ROI) of the depth image and linearly scales forward velocity down to a minimum of 20% when the minimum depth in the ROI falls below 1.5 m. This provides gradual deceleration as obstacles approach, rather than abrupt stopping that could destabilise the vehicle. Third, altitude guarding monitors the UAV's altitude and flags deviations exceeding 1.0 m from the target altitude, which could indicate a sensor failure or environmental disturbance. Fourth, emergency stop zeroes all velocity commands upon collision detection or communications timeout exceeding 500 ms, providing a last-resort safety net.

The safety monitor is architecturally separate from the policy: it receives the policy's commands as input and outputs modified commands to the flight controller. This separation ensures that the safety guarantees do not depend on the policy's behaviour and can be verified independently through unit testing (the test suite includes dedicated safety monitor tests). During training, the safety monitor is disabled to allow the agent to experience the consequences of unsafe actions and learn to avoid them. During deployment, the monitor is mandatory.

### 3.7 Sim-to-Real Transfer Pipeline

The trained policy is exported to ONNX format using a custom export script that traces the MultiInputPolicy's forward pass with representative input tensors. The ONNX model is optimised for the NVIDIA Jetson Xavier NX onboard the Quanser QDrone 2 using TensorRT, targeting greater than 30 Hz inference to exceed the 10 Hz control loop rate with margin. The deployment architecture uses two ROS2 nodes: rl_inference (subscribing to depth camera and VIO topics, publishing velocity commands) and safety_monitor (subscribing to velocity commands, applying all four safety layers, publishing safe commands to the flight controller via MAVLink). The Intel RealSense D435i provides both depth images and infrared stereo pairs for VIO computation.

[PLACEHOLDER: Figure 2 -- ROS2 node graph showing rl_inference, safety_monitor, and QDrone 2 flight controller communication via MAVLink. Include topic names and message types.]

