## 4. Implementation

### 4.1 AirSim Environment Wrapper

The AirSimDroneEnv class wraps the AirSim Python API as a Gymnasium-compatible environment, enabling direct integration with Stable-Baselines3 training algorithms. The wrapper implements lockstep simulation: at each step, the simulation is paused (simPause(True)), an action is received, the velocity command is issued via moveByVelocityZBodyFrameAsync, the simulation advances by dt = 0.1 s via simContinueForTime(dt), and the new observation is captured. This ensures deterministic training regardless of the host machine's computational speed.

The reset protocol addresses several AirSim-specific challenges. First, the simulation must be unpaused before reset, as blocking API calls hang on a paused simulation. Second, simSetVehiclePose is called with ignore_collision=True and a retry loop (5 attempts) to handle rare cases where the vehicle spawns inside geometry. Third, a 0.5 s physics settling delay is applied after teleportation to allow transient forces to dissipate. Collision detection uses timestamp-based filtering: a collision is only counted if the AirSim collision API's time_stamp field has changed since the last check, preventing stale collision flags from the previous episode from terminating the new one.

Body-frame velocity is computed by rotating AirSim's NED global-frame kinematics into the body frame using the current yaw angle. When the simulated VIO module is enabled, this ground-truth velocity is passed through SimulatedVIO before being returned as part of the observation. The entire wrapper, including VIO integration, domain randomisation hooks, and multi-waypoint navigation logic, is validated by 147 unit tests that run without AirSim by mocking the AirSim client at the API boundary.

### 4.2 PPO Training Pipeline

Training uses the Stable-Baselines3 [24] implementation of PPO with the following hyperparameters: learning rate 3e-4, n_steps 2048 (rollout buffer size), batch size 64, 10 optimisation epochs per rollout, discount factor gamma = 0.99, GAE lambda = 0.95, clip range 0.2, entropy coefficient 0.01, and total timesteps ranging from 500K (fast profile) to 1M (standard profile). The MultiInputPolicy uses a NatureCNN feature extractor [26] for the depth image branch (three convolutional layers with 32, 64, 64 filters and strides 4, 2, 1, followed by a 512-unit fully connected layer) and a two-layer MLP (64, 64 units with ReLU activation) for the velocity branch. The features from both branches are concatenated (late fusion) before being passed to the shared actor and critic heads.

Training supports parallel execution via SubprocVecEnv with N simultaneous AirSim instances on consecutive API ports (base_port through base_port + N - 1), providing approximately linear speedup in environment sampling. For N = 1, a DummyVecEnv is used for simplicity. Checkpoints are saved every 10,000 steps, and the best model is selected by evaluation reward computed over 5 deterministic episodes every 5,000 training steps. Training can be resumed from any checkpoint by loading the saved model and environment normalisation statistics. Multi-environment rotation between AirSim Neighbourhood and Blocks environments is supported via an EnvironmentScheduler callback that switches the active environment every 50 episodes.

### 4.3 Evaluation Protocol

The standardised evaluation protocol runs 20 episodes per campaign with fixed random seeds for reproducibility. Seven metrics are computed: collision rate (fraction of episodes ending in collision), average speed (mean forward velocity in m/s), path smoothness (mean jerk magnitude in m/s^3, computed from second differences of velocity), survival time (mean episode duration in seconds before collision or timeout), time to goal (mean timesteps to reach waypoint, for waypoint tasks), trajectory RMSE (root mean square deviation from a reference path in metres), and localisation drift (Euclidean distance between VIO-estimated and ground-truth position at episode end, in metres). Results are saved as JSON files with per-episode data to enable post-hoc statistical analysis. Cross-experiment comparison is supported by a dedicated plotting module that generates multi-metric bar charts with confidence intervals.

### 4.4 Software Engineering Practices

The codebase follows professional software engineering standards to ensure reliability and reproducibility. All 147 unit tests are AirSim-free, using mocked API clients, and cover reward functions, safety monitor logic, evaluation metrics, PID controllers, domain randomisation, and cross-experiment comparison. The ruff linter enforces consistent code style with zero outstanding errors. The project includes 14 YAML configuration files organised by purpose (training profiles, reward weights, environment settings, ablation configs) and 4 training profiles (base, fast, domain randomisation, multi-environment). An automated ablation suite (scripts/run_ablations.py) executes 7 experiments across 4 axes (reward components, frame stack depth, domain randomisation, VIO drift), and a reward sweep script (scripts/run_reward_sweep.py) compares 3 reward weight profiles (default, aggressive, cautious). All hyperparameters are specified in YAML configuration files; none are hardcoded in source files.

